**Non-force fetch can silently do nothing when local refs diverge**

The comment on line 105 says "non-force to avoid destroying local work," but `git fetch` with a non-force refspec will simply *refuse* the update if the remote has diverged (non-fast-forward). The error is logged to stderr and swallowed — the server continues as if nothing happened, with stale local refs. There is no mechanism to detect or surface this divergence to the user.

At minimum, failed fetches due to divergence should be logged at a higher severity or tracked so the user can be alerted. Silently running with stale data is arguably worse than force-updating.